  &preamble;

  <sect1 id="prereq">
    <title>Build Prerequisites</title>

    <para>&YP; was designed to have only few library dependencies, and to build on most
      popular Unices.</para>

    <sect2 id="supportedplatforms">
      <title>Supported Platforms</title>

      <para>&YP; was successfully built on following platforms:</para>
      <itemizedlist>
	<listitem><simpara>FreeBSD</simpara></listitem>
	<listitem><simpara>Linux</simpara></listitem>
	<listitem><simpara>Sun Solaris 10 x86</simpara></listitem>
	<listitem><simpara>Cygwin</simpara></listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </sect2>

    <sect2 id="requiredlibraries">
      <title>Required Libraries</title>

      <para>&YP; depends on two libraries</para>
      <itemizedlist>

	<listitem>
	  <simpara><ulink url="http://www.openssl.org">openssl</ulink></simpara></listitem>
	<listitem>
	  <simpara>curses or
	  <ulink url="http://http://www.gnu.org/software/ncurses/">ncurses</ulink></simpara> </listitem>
      </itemizedlist>
    </sect2>

  </sect1>

  <sect1 id="buildinstr">
    <title>Brief Build Instructions</title>

    <para>&YP; uses a <command>configure</command> script as generated
      by <command>autoconf</command> and friends for configuring the
      build process of &YP;. Change to the directory where you
      unpacked <filename>&YPPKG;</filename> and simply type</para>

    <para>
<screen>
  <prompt>#</prompt> <literal>./configure</literal>
</screen>
    </para>

    <para>on the command line. The configure script will then check
      the system an prepares for the build process.
    </para>

    <para>If the <command>configure</command> script successfully
    finishes, type</para>

    <para>
<screen>
  <prompt>#</prompt> <literal>make</literal>
</screen>
    </para>

    <para>&YP; will now be builded. After the build has finished,
      switch to the root user if not done already, and type
    </para>

    <para>
<screen>
  <prompt>#</prompt> <literal>make install</literal>
</screen>
    </para>

    <para>This will install &YP; into
      the <filename>/usr/local/bin</filename> directory, if the prefix
      has not been changed by providing
      <option>--prefix=<literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal></option> to
      the <command>configure</command> script.</para>

    <para>To start &YP; issue
      <filename>/usr/local/bin</filename>/<command>yapet</command> on
      the command line.</para>
  </sect1>

  <sect1 id="confoptions">
    <title>Brief configure Options Description</title>

    <variablelist>
      <varlistentry>
	<term>
	  <option>--prefix=</option><literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal>
	</term>

	<listitem>
	  <para><literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal> is the base directory
	    where &YP; will be installed. The executable is installed in
	    <literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal><filename>/bin</filename>.
	  </para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
	<term>
	  <option>--with-xsl-sheet=</option><literal>&lt;FILE&gt;</literal>
	</term>

	<listitem>
	  <para><literal>&lt;FILE&gt;</literal> is the file path of
	    the XSL Style Sheet to use for generating documentation
	    files. More specifically, this is the file fed
	    to <command>xsltproc</command> for generating some of the
	    documenation files (this file for instance) from the
	    docbook source. This option is only used
	    if <command>xsltproc</command> and <command>lynx</command>
	    are found by <command>configure</command>.</para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
	<term>
	  <option>--with-curses-include=</option><literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal>
	</term>

	<listitem><para>This option tells the compiler where to find the
	    header files of
	    curses/ncurses. <literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal> has to be the
	    directory where the header files are located, not the file
	    name of the header file.</para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
	<term>
	  <option>--with-curses-lib=</option><literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal>
	</term>

	<listitem>
	  <para>This option tells the linker where to find the
	    curses/ncurses shared
	    library. <literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal> has to be the
	    directory where the shared library is located, not the file
	    name of the shared library.</para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
	<term>
	  <option>--with-openssl-include=</option><literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal>
	</term>

	<listitem>
	  <para>This options tells the compiler where to find the
	    header files of openssl. <literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal> has to be the
	    directory where the header files are located, not the file
	    name of the header file.</para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>

      <varlistentry>
	<term>
	  <option>--with-openssl-lib=</option><literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal>
	</term>

	<listitem>
	  <para>This option tells the linker where to find the
	    openssl shared
	    library. <literal>&lt;PATH&gt;</literal> has to be the
	    directory where the shared library is located, not the file
	    name of the shared library.</para>
	</listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>
  </sect1>

  <sect1 id="furtherinfo">
    <title>Further Information</title>

    <para>For more information about the configure script, read the
      file <filename>INSTALL.generic</filename> which comes along in the
      tarball of &YP;.</para>
  </sect1>

</article>

